We need to evaluate if visualization is misleading based on description. The description: line chart with x days 0-90, y -2% to -20%. It says percentage decline from baseline, negative values (decline). Axis range seems not starting at zero, but since it's decline, zero would be no decline; they start at -2% to -20% (i.e., truncated axis? Actually they exclude -0% to -2% region). Starting at -2% not zero could exaggerate differences? Since all values are negative, starting at -2% could still be okay but could truncate small declines. Might be considered truncated axis because not starting at zero (0% decline). That could mislead magnitude? The lines are close maybe. Also interquartile shading.

Potential issues: Cherry-picking? They show only first 90 days, not longer; might ignore later rebound. But not necessarily cherry-picking, maybe just scope.

Interpretation claims lockdowns more effective; but causality? The chart shows correlation; the text says "lockdowns are a more powerful tool for reducing mobility (and likely, transmission) compared to voluntary social distancing." That's causal inference from observational data. So Causal inference error.

Also they claim "Developing Economies demonstrate the least amount of decline ... This could indicate a greater difficulty ...". That's interpretation, but okay.

Potential misrepresentation: The y-axis negative direction may be confusing; but they use negative decline, blue below orange indicates more decline (more negative). Might be Inverted axis? Usually decline could be positive magnitude; but they use negative numbers, which may invert perception (more negative = larger decline). Could be considered "Inverted axis" because direction of value (more negative down) might be confusing.

But main errors: Truncated axis (doesn't start at 0% decline), Causal inference, possibly Cherry-picking (only first 90 days). Also maybe Failure to account for statistical nuance? They use interquartile range but no mention of significance.

Thus is visualization misleading? Likely yes due to causal inference and axis truncation. Confidence maybe 80.

Intentional? Likely somewhat intentional to emphasize lockdown effect; could be purposeful framing. Confidence maybe 65.

Now rhetoric types: Information Access Rhetoric: choices of showing only 0-90 days, only three groups, using interquartile shading; yes exists. Supports misleading (by focusing early period). Confidence 85.

Provenance Rhetoric: they cite sources (Google, Oxford, IMF) in caption. So exists. Supports misleading? maybe not directly but gives authority; could support misleading by lending credibility. Confidence 75.

Mapping Rhetoric: mapping decline to vertical position (negative). Also color choice. Exists. Might support misleading by using negative axis that can mislead magnitude. Confidence 80.

Linguistic-Based Rhetoric: title/caption language claims causality, "effectiveness", etc. Exists. Supports misleading. Confidence 85.

Procedural Rhetoric: No interactive features described; likely none. So not exists.
